<p><b>ARM</b> is a family of <a href="/w/index.php?title=bi-endian&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="bi-endian (page does not exist)">bi-endian</a> <a href="/w/index.php?title=fixed-length&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="fixed-length (page does not exist)">fixed-length</a> <a href="/w/index.php?title=instruction_set_architectures&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="instruction set architectures (page does not exist)">instruction set architectures</a> and extensions. The ARM architecture is widely used in the <a href="/w/index.php?title=mobile&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="mobile (page does not exist)">mobile</a> and <a href="/w/index.php?title=embedded&action=edit&redlink=1" class="new" title="embedded (page does not exist)">embedded</a> markets. Today, ARM-based implementations are designed by a number of <a href="/wiki/semiconductor_companies" class="mw-redirect" title="semiconductor companies">companies</a> including <a href="/wiki/ARM_Holdings" class="mw-redirect" title="ARM Holdings">ARM Holdings</a>, <a href="/wiki/Qualcomm" class="mw-redirect" title="Qualcomm">Qualcomm</a>, <a href="/wiki/Apple" class="mw-redirect" title="Apple">Apple</a>, and <a href="/wiki/AppliedMicro" class="mw-redirect" title="AppliedMicro">AppliedMicro</a>.
